A case of the application of Non Evaporable Getter (NEG) pumps to fusion devices is discussed. Compared with  
other pumping technologies used in fusion devices, the NEG pumps have advantages in terms of operation  
temperature at 100–200 °C (in which there is a high tolerance of the temperature increase due to a plasma  
radiation and/or an unexpected heat load from heating devices), low power consumption and compactness.  
Moreover, in the case of a power outage getters continue pumping and do not release hydrogen and its isotopes.  
The NEG pumps have been installed as an in-vessel pump into the divertor region in the Large Helical Device  
3
(
LHD) for the ﬁrst time. The pumping performance test shows that the eﬀective pumping speed is 10 m /s in  
hydrogen, which is close to the target value. In addition, the exposure of the NEG pumps to boronization and  
glow discharge treatments have been tested. While the boronization and glow discharge under noble gases do  
not show eﬀect on the pumping performances of the NEG pumps, the establishment of an operational scenario  
including hydrogen and deuterium glow discharges consistent with other pumping facilities is still an aspect to  
be reﬁned. However, the use of NEG pumps in LHD divertor is a milestone for the possibility of using this  
technology in future fusion devices.

1. Introduction

A vacuum pump is an essential tool in order to exhaust and control  
the divertor cryo-sorption pump. The target of the divertor pumping  
speed is 100 m /s, which is balanced with the fueling throughput of  
10 Hz ice pellet if the divertor pressure is assumed to be 1 Pa [6]. In  
order to reach this target, further development of the divertor pumping  
is planned in the LHD.  
Cryo-sorption pumps are clearly one of the most robust vacuum  
pumps. However, these pumps are not versatile because the sustain-  
ment of the cryogenic state (< 20 K) is not easy during the plasma  
discharges. The protection from the plasma radiation should be care-  
fully considered in order not to increase the temperature of the cryo  
panels. As a result, the restriction might limit the conductance of the  
pump. Also, in the case of the cryo-sorption pump facing the plasma  
heating device such as ECH, the temperature may increase due to un-  
expected not-absorbed micro waves. Therefore, there is room for other  
vacuum pumping systems to be applied as in-vessel pumps. In this  
study, Non Evaporable Getter (NEG) pumps are introduced to the di-  
vertor pumps. The features of the NEG pumps are shown in detail in  
3
neutral particles in fusion plasmas. So far, in many vacuum layouts of  
fusion devices cryogenic pumps such as cryo-sorption and cryo-con-  
densation, turbo molecular pumps and mechanical pumps are utilized  
as standard solutions. In the International Thermonuclear Experimental  
Reactor (ITER) project, the manufacturing of the ﬁrst torus cyro-sorp-  
tion pump has been recently reported [1].  
The pumping eﬃciency of the vacuum pumps depends on the va-  
cuum pressure and pumping speed. In order to obtain the highest  
pumping eﬃciency, higher compression of the neutral particles and  
higher pumping speed are required. In the Large Helical Device (LHD)  
[
2], which is one of the largest superconducting fusion devices among  
helical systems, the closed divertor system has been developed and  
installed in order to attain higher neutral compression in the inner di-  
vertor sections [3]. Moreover, in order to exhaust the compressed  
neutral particles, in-vessel divertor pumps have been developed step by  
step [4,5]. In the divertor pumps, the cryo-sorption pump is utilized and

ments was in TFTR as a limiter operation [8]. New interest has emerged  
regarding the use of NEG pumps since 2014 with the development of  
the new patented ZAO getter alloy [11,12]. This getter material, due to  
its high aﬃnity for hydrogenic species, large capacity and robustness, is  
a promising candidate for application in fusion devices. One of the most  
notable advantages is represented by their operation temperature,  
which ranges from room temperature to 100–200 °C or higher. This  
means that the NEG pumps have a high tolerance for temperature in-  
crease. As a result, an enlargement of the conductance without the  
requirement of the protection from the plasma radiation is possible. In  
this paper, the installation of NEG pumps to the LHD divertor region  
and their pumping performance will be described.  
Based on the installation design, the NEG pumps were successfully  
assembled and fabricated in the LHD. In the next section, the heat load  
on reactivation/regeneration processes to the ﬁrst wall of the vacuum  
vessel will be discussed.  
2. Application of NEG pumps to divertor pumping in the LHD  
2.2. Simulation of heat load from NEG pumps to ﬁrst wall

.1. Design of the installation of NEG pumps  
After the installation, NEG pumps need an activation procedure to  
achieve their nominal pumping speed [14]. In addition, in applications  
with high load of hydrogen isotopes like fusion devices, the capacity for  
these gases must be regenerated after some time depending on the  
experimental conditions, installation geometry and available NEG ma-  
terial [14]. Although the operation temperature of NEG pumps during  
working conditions is between room temperature and 100–200 °C, the  
operation temperature during reactivation/regeneration processes is  
more than 500 °C. The ﬁrst wall of the vacuum vessel in the LHD must  
be kept under 95 °C during the plasma experiments due to the restric-  
tion of the heat insulation properties of the superconducting coils. In  
this section the heat load from the NEG pumps to the ﬁrst wall is dis-  
cussed.  
In order to evaluate the temperature increase of the ﬁrst wall  
against the radiation heat ﬂux of HV400 wafer modules, the heat load  
was analyzed using a ﬁnite element method based software for multi-  
physics analysis (ANSYS). In the analysis, other viscous heat transfer  
eﬀects (conduction and convection) are not assumed because the  
pressure is kept at high vacuum during the reactivation/regeneration  
processes. The model geometry is shown in Fig. 2(a) and (b). In order to  
reduce the heat intrusion due to a plasma radiation, the ﬁrst wall is  
covered with stainless plates 10 mm in thickness, and is cooled by the  
cooling channels attached on the ﬁrst wall. Regarding the thermal  
boundary conditions, the surface temperature of the HV400 wafer  
module during an activation process is ﬁxed at 400 °C. The water  
temperature in the cooling channel is ﬁxed at 25 °C in standard con-  
ditions. We can approximate the value for the heat transfer coeﬃcient  
between the inner surface of the cooling channel and the coolant water  
In the LHD, there are ten toroidal divertor sections. In ﬁve out of ten  
sections, in-vessel cryo-sorption pumps are already installed. In one of  
these divertor sections, the installation design of the NEG pumps is  
investigated as a proto-type. The target pumping speed for the NEG  
pumps is set up at 10 m /s for hydrogen, because this target value  
means a total pumping speed of 100 m /s if we assume the installation  
of NEG pumps in all of the toroidal sections. The HV400 wafer module  
produced by SAES Getters S.p.A. was applied as shown in Fig. 1(a). The

3. Pumping performance  
3.1. Reactivation/regeneration process  
After the absorption of a signiﬁcant amount of gases, in order to  
recover the original pumping performance NEG pumps need to be he-  
ated up to about 500 °C. Two basic processes occur during the treat-  
ment: on one side, the active species as nitrogen, oxygen and carbon  
oxides, which are chemically bound on the surface, diﬀuse into the bulk  
material, thus freeing the adsorption sites. This process is commonly  
called reactivation and requires from one to two hours to be completed.  
On the other side, at high temperature hydrogenic species are extracted  
from the bulk material, following the laws of isothermal equilibrium.  
This is the so-called regeneration process, which duration depends on  
several factors such as temperature, the getter mass, the available  
auxiliary pumping speed and the initial and ﬁnal hydrogen con-  
centrations.  
Fig. 4 shows the typical time trend during the regeneration in LHD.  
In order to obtain an eﬃcient regeneration process, an eﬃcient aux-  
iliary pumping system and the temperature are the key parameters

and turbo molecular pumps are used in the LHD and the total pumping

The diﬀerence of the pumping speed might be attributed to the tem-  
perature condition during the activation. In the ﬁrst activation, the

5. Conclusion  
The installation of in-vessel Non Evaporable Getter (NEG) pumps to  
the LHD divertor region and their pumping performance are in-  
vestigated. The compact HV400 wafer module produced by SAES  
Getters S.p.A. was applied to the in-vessel divertor pump. The in-  
stallation of the in-vessel NEG pumps, which consist of 42 modules, was  
completed in one section as a prototype. The total installed pumping

. Discussion of the operation scenario of NEG pumps  
The temperature during reactivation/regeneration processes is more  
than 500 °C. The heat load from the NEG pumps to the ﬁrst wall was  
analyzed using ANSYS. The analysis shows that the local temperature of  
the ﬁrst wall is less than 70 °C at maximum, which is within the ap-  
proved temperature limit of 95 °C due to the restriction of the super-  
conducting coil. In order to evaluate the eﬃcient pumping speed, the  
conductance of the HV400 wafer module was evaluated using the fully  
three-dimensional neutral particle transport simulation code EIRENE.
